<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 92 / Bucking the Trend: Bogus customers produce genuine profits -
Guy de Jonquieres explains how a market research company has grown rapidly
despite the recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT A TIME when British companies are paring costs to the bone, asking them
to spend as much as Pounds 200,000 a year to serve bogus customers hardly
sounds like a winning formula. Yet it is providing BEM Research, a small
market research company, with the basis for a business that has thrived
through the recession.
BEM specialises in measuring customer service. Formed six years ago by three
partners with no market research experience, it now has more than 60
clients, for many of which it monitors service standards continuously.
They include the Automobile Association, electrical retailers Comet, Currys
and Dixons, Ladbroke's betting shops, McDonald's hamburger restaurants, the
Forte hotel and leisure group, several local councils and a clutch of
regional electricity boards.
The company has doubled turnover every year to reach Pounds 2m this year, on
which it will earn profits of Pounds 170,000, up from Pounds 36,000 last
year and Pounds 18,000 in 1990. UK market research spending as a whole
stagnated last year, although it has recovered since the spring.
BEM's special edge is the use of 'mystery' customers, who visit retail
outlets unannounced. Drawn from a team of 2,000 part-time researchers, they
are trained to evaluate service by acting as ordinary members of the public.
Mr Steve Jolliffe, managing director, says BEM has prospered during
recession because it delivers immediate feedback to its clients and
identifies cost-effective ways of improving customer satisfaction.
His claim is endorsed by Mr Martin Grant, managing director of Ansells
Retail, part of Allied Lyons: 'When times are tough, the most important
priority is to keep the business you've got. BEM has done so well because it
provides a tool which helps companies retain customers.'
Ansells says its 600 managed pubs have increased market share in the two
years since BEM began monitoring them and highlighted the importance to
customers of points such as clean lavatories and friendly bar service.
Mr Jolliffe, a 34-year-old former mining engineer, hit on the idea for
'mystery' customers - and decided to make a business out of it - after
receiving poor service at a restaurant several years ago. Incensed, he wrote
to the parent company recommending improvements. Many were put into effect,
and he was invited to survey other restaurants in the chain.
Since then, the technique has been refined. Before carrying out research,
BEM asks clients' customers what kind of service they expect and involves
employees in setting objectives.
Other market research companies, some of which initially frowned on
'mystery' customers, have begun to use the technique. But Mr Jolliffe is
confident that BEM can maintain its lead by continuing to invest in people
and technology.
'Our competitors have lots of resources but little experience. They use
trained interviewers who are used to holding clipboards and are easily
spotted. Our mystery customers only do one thing,' he says.
</TEXT>
