<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 92 / Managers report career worries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES ARE failing to manage their managers and leaving a big gap between
company rhetoric and reality as perceived by middle managers, the Institute
of Management says.
A survey published by the institute today warns that if the gap is not
closed it might have long-term consequences for company performance as
managers' disillusionment grows. Organisations are increasingly focusing
reward systems on individual performance, yet half of the managers surveyed
believe their own pay packets bear little relation to their actual
contribution.
Few organisations have thought through the implications of reconciling the
trend towards more team working with the increased emphasis on rewarding
managers' individual performance. Any change to pay and benefits is largely
imposed from the top down. Fifty two per cent of individual respondents said
they had not been involved in developing plans for change.
Two thirds of managers believe their organisation pays insufficient
attention to their career management and development and two thirds are
worried about promotion.
Who's Managing the Managers? IM Books, Burston Distribution Services, 2A
Newbridge Trading Estate, Whitby Road, Bristol BS4 4AX. Pounds 30 to
non-members, Pounds 15 to members.
</TEXT>
