<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 92 / Mortgage cover causes concern
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT said yesterday that it was concerned about a planned change
in mortgage indemnity insurance that would make it difficult for the owners
of private flats in local-authority tower blocks to sell their properties.
The main mortgage indemnity insurers are negotiating with lenders to tighten
policies so that societies will normally be unable to get insurance for
mortgages on former council flats in blocks above seven storeys in height.
The Department of the Environment said it was worried about the
'seven-storey clause', put to lenders in a contract drawn up by four
insurance companies. It said it had made representations to the Council of
Mortgage Lenders. The clause would be awkward for the government because it
would limit the value of council flats bought under 'right-to-buy
legislation'. Although flats were sold at discount, it might cut their value
below that price.
The clause is among a series being negotiated between insurers and lenders.
The insurers are estimated to have lost Pounds 3bn in the wave of house
repossessions of the past three years, including defaults among former
council tenants, while gaining only Pounds 750m in premiums. Legal &amp;
General, one of the four companies providing most indemnity insurance, said
it would insist on keeping the clause, which would make lenders seek
approval for mortgages on council-block flats in order to gain insurance.
Mr Dane Douetil, a director of Special Risk Services, a Lloyd's insurance
broker, said the talks were causing 'a great deal of tension' because
insurers were insisting on indemnity policies becoming both more expensive
and restrictive.
The main terms of new mortgage indemnity contracts were agreed by insurers
and lenders in September. They replaced the old formula for indemnity
payments with one that makes lenders bear at least 20 per cent of the loss.
The insurers have insisted that lenders bear some of the future loss to make
them take more care over lending. The two sides were unable to agree the
subsidiary clauses by September, though, and a new deadline for agreement of
January has been set. Among the clauses are provisions to end insurers'
liability if lenders are defrauded by borrowers.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, chairman of the Council of Mortgage Lenders, said the
lenders understood that insurers wanted to tighten the terms of mortgage
indemnity insurance, but it was likely to lead to restrictions in lending.
</TEXT>
