<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 92 / Principality deserts Swiss lead with vote for EEA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VADUZ
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MOUSE roared in alpine Europe yesterday when the tiny principality of
Liechtenstein defied public opinion in neighbouring Switzerland and voted to
join the European Economic Area.
In traditional Ruritanian style, Mr Hans Brunhart, the prime minister,
offered a news conference dominated by Swiss journalists the joking pledge
that this would not mean border posts being put up on the country's eastern
Rhine frontier - 'at least not tomorrow.'
The outcome, nonetheless, was quite as surprising to many Liechtensteiners
as Switzerland's vote just a week earlier not to join the EEA, the free
trade accord widely seen as a waiting room for the European Community.
Most of Liechtenstein's political leaders had warned before the Swiss
plebiscite that - whatever its result - their country should follow their
neighbour's lead. But when the Swiss voted No, Vaduz was caught between
solidarity with Berne and its need to trade in a wider Europe to defend an
industrial base accounting for a remarkable 50 per cent of gross domestic
product. In the event, the outcome was decisive, with all 12 communes
obeying Prince Hans Adam II's impassioned entreaties for a Yes vote.
The overall majority was exactly 1,400 votes - a wafer in a UK constituency,
but a landslide in a country of just 30,000.
The consequences, nonetheless, may be significant for the 70-year-old
customs union with Switzerland. Hurried assurances were issued last night
that the vote will not materially affect relations with the Swiss nor
involve surrendering the mighty Swiss franc as Liechtenstein's national
currency.
The principality's businessmen and international bankers have also been
promised that there is no threat to its much-envied low-tax regime that has
helped make it the richest country in Europe in terms of GDP per capita.
Talks will open soon with Switzerland on how to adjust the terms of the
customs union to accommodate both sides.
Last night, the Prince was clearly jubilant at his subjects' independence of
spirit. But he insisted that the outcome was not so much a rejection of
Switzerland as a solid endorsement of closer trade ties with a wider Europe
that buys 45 per cent of Liechtenstein's manufactured exports.
Questioned on possible EC membership, the Prince rejected a membership
application as 'a step too far.'
That will come as a relief to the lightly-taxed drinkers celebrating or
drowning their sorrows last night in the Old Castle inn in downtown Vaduz.
Whatever their views they were united in a determination not to be drawn
into a system which might force them to bail out their, in comparative
terms, impoverished northern near-neighbours - the Germans.
</TEXT>
