<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 92 / Italian polls set to test old parties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MUNICIPAL elections yesterday and today in 55 Italian cities and towns will
provide the first serious test of electoral opinion in the country since the
April general elections.
The main focus is on the towns of Monza and Varese in the Milan industrial
belt, where opinion polls show the populist Lombard League is likely to
consolidate its position as the main political party in northern Italy.
At the small town of Fiumicino, near Rome, the first trial cross-party
alliance is being tested with reformist elements of the Christian Democrat
Party headed by Mr Mario Segni, a progressive sector of the Socialist Party
loyal to Mr Claudio Martelli, justice minister, and sympathisers among the
former communist Party of the Democratic Left (PDS).
All the parties are in a state of flux, the main ascendant being the
anti-Rome Lombard League which has burst on the scene in the past 18 months
with limited funds but profiting from public disillusion with a corrupt
political establishment.
The extent of the slippage in support for the Christian Democrats and
Socialists will demonstrate how far the electorate has decided to desert
these two parties.
