<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 92 / Summit success paves way for EC enlargement: Edinburgh pact
on Community financing Danish opt-outs agreed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   EDINBURGH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENTS in the European Community yesterday hailed the success of the
weekend summit at Edinburgh, saying it would provide a road map for the
Community's political development to the end of the century.
Mr John Major, UK prime minister who chaired the EC heads of government
meeting, declared that it would go down 'as the summit that put the
Community back together'.
Leaders of the 12 agreed on the crucial issues of future EC financing and
the Danish question, building a platform from which to relaunch the
Community in 1993 through immediate enlargement negotiations with Austria,
Sweden and Finland.
In spite of continuing turbulence in the currency market, EC officials said
they believed that the wide-ranging agreements in Edinburgh would restore
faith in the goal of a single currency by the end of the decade.
The Community faced an 'all or nothing' summit in which the much criticised
UK presidency had to pull off a series of interlocking deals on the EC
budget and Denmark's demands for legally-binding exemptions from the
Maastricht treaty. It also had to demonstrate to the citizens of Europe that
the EC could recover from the crisis triggered by Danish voters' rejection
of the treaty last June.
Thanks to the Edinburgh agreement, Denmark intends to resubmit the treaty to
its voters by May at the latest. The Copenhagen minority government is
confident of approval.
Copenhagen got everything it asked for at Edinburgh, declared Mr Poul
Schluter, its prime minister. In Denmark, the Edinburgh agreement was
welcomed by business leaders and greeted by newspaper headlines such as
'Triumph for Denmark' and 'Europe Gave Way'.
The country's leftwing Socialist People's party joined two other opposition
parties in declaring support for the deal. The party's executive committee
took the decision, after a five-hour meeting, to go along with the Social
Democrat and Radical Liberal parties, in backing the accord. This gives it
the backing of seven of the eight parties in the Folketing, the Danish
parliament.
Mr Major pledged to complete ratification of the treaty in the House of
Commons 'hard on the heels' of the Danish vote.
EC leaders agreed to make the Community more accountable through more
decentralised and open decision-making. They also presented a modest growth
package which calls for co-ordination of national macroeconomic policy and
increased spending at EC level on capital investment, roads,
telecommunications and infrastructure.
The two-day meeting was marked by tough bargaining. It was 'very hard going
and tense', according to prime minister Felipe Gonzalez of Spain who at one
stage during bilateral talks with Mr Major on Saturday threatened to walk
out.
Under the budget deal, EC leaders agreed to raise annual Community spending
from Ecu66.8bn (Pounds 52.7bn) in 1992 to Ecu84bn in 1999, in today's money.
The main winners are poorer EC members, led by Spain, which will receive
roughly double the amount of development aid. The finance agreement was
hailed by Mr Jacques Delors, European Commission president, who said he got
'85 per cent' of what he sought. But the policies developed by Brussels in
recent years will suffer as a result of the concessions to Spain, Portugal,
Greece and Ireland.
EC leaders expressed frustration over delays in ratifying the treaty.
Denmark and Britain were warned by EC leaders, including President Francois
Mitterrand, that they wanted ratification by summer. German foreign minister
Klaus Kinkel said: 'The fate of European union, which we have agreed upon in
Edinburgh, now lies in the hands of Britain and Denmark.'
