FT  14 DEC 92 / Key decisions at Edinburgh EC Summit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
DENMARK: Denmark exempted from key aims of Maastricht treaty - single
currency and common defence - clearing way for second Danish referendum next
year.
BUDGET: Seven-year deal freezing ceiling on resources at 1.2 per cent of GDP
for two years with phased increases to 1.27 per cent by 1999. Fund for four
poorest states - Spain, Portugal, Ireland and Greece - worth Ecu 15.15bn
(Pounds 12.1bn) over seven years.
ENLARGEMENT: Negotiations to open from January 1 with Austria, Sweden and
Finland. Talks with Norway start later next year.
GROWTH: Growth initiative through infrastructure development worth up to
Dollars 37bn (Pounds 23.7bn) via lending facility at European Investment
Bank and European Investment Fund.
SUBSIDIARITY: Procedures to apply principle of subsidiarity, under which EC
acts only when member states cannot achieve goal as well themselves.
TRANSPARENCY: Some ministerial meetings televised and details of votes
published. EC laws made clearer.
SITES OF INSTITUTIONS: Sites of existing institutions confirmed. Countries
with no EC institution to have priority for new ones
MEMBERS OF EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT: Germany receives 18 more members.
YUGOSLAVIA: Pressure on Serbia and Bosnian Serbs, systematic rape of Moslem
women in Bosnia condemned, Macedonia offered economic aid but not
recognition under present name.
RUSSIA: Strong support expressed for Yeltsin's reform programme.
