<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 92 / Yeltsin wins deal to pursue economic reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE RUSSIAN government expects to press on with its economic and democratic
reforms following President Boris Yeltsin's compromise at the weekend with
the Congress of People's Deputies, the conservative-dominated parliament.
The deal with Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the conservative chairman of
parliament, extends Mr Yeltsin's special powers, enabling him to select his
prime minister from a Congress shortlist.
Hailed by supporters as a victory, it also fixes a date for a referendum on
constitutional change, paving the way for the first fully elected Russian
parliament.
Where the government was previously expected to survive at most until next
April, it is now Congress and the Supreme Soviet, its smaller permanent
body, which are under notice, since a new constitution would call for fresh
elections to a new parliamentary body. Father Gleb Yakunin, a prominent
liberal deputy, said 'the president now has a big advantage'.
The long-term survival of Mr Yegor Gaidar, acting prime minister and
guardian of economic reform, is still uncertain, but Mr Yeltsin could
confirm him in the post for a further three months if he is rejected in a
Congress vote, as he was narrowly last week.
Deputies will vote, probably today, on a slate of candidates to select a
shortlist of three from which Mr Yeltsin will choose a prime minister.
Many deputies, even Mr Gaidar's opponents, expect him to win at least a
temporary continuation of his post. But the government is also discussing
the idea that Mr Gaidar could move to head economic reform, something to
which he has been unable to give his full attention since becoming prime
minister.
Senior ministers and advisers said over the weekend that they believed the
deal, which fixed the date for a referendum on a new constitution on April
11, had raised the perspective for a new era in Russian politics - with a
modern democratic constitution underpinning an elected parliament with its
powers clearly defined.
One said: 'In effect, the Congress were persuaded to vote themselves out of
existence.' The Congress, with the Supreme Soviet, is a holdover from the
Soviet era - as is the much amended constitution.
However, there is concern the new government may have too little support to
push through a tougher line on credits and money supply to crack down on
rising inflation and a large budget deficit.
Mr Yeltsin emerged from his meeting with Mr Khasbulatov with:
A constitutional referendum, with the right to frame his own question if he
cannot agree it with Congress.
An extension of his special powers, allowing him to appoint a prime
minister, who must be confirmed by Congress, and issue decrees.
The commitment from the Congress not to change the power balance between it,
the president and the judiciary by changing the constitution, or the
referendum law, or elect judges to the two vacant seats on the
Constitutional Court.
The Congress won nothing on economic reform, with its gains confined to
personnel changes. It achieved:
The right to nominate and vote for alternative candidates for prime
minister.
The right, won earlier last week, to vote on the ministers of foreign
affairs, security, defence and interior. The sacking of Mr Gennady Burbulis,
closest aide to Mr Yeltsin, who has had several changes of title in the
past.
Seeking to bolster aid, Page 4
</TEXT>
