<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 92 / Somali warlords agree to immediate ceasefire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE, DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOGADISHU, BRUSSELS, LITTLE ROCK, ARKANSAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOMALIA'S two main warlords, who have plunged the country into anarchy and
starvation over the past two years, yesterday agreed an immediate ceasefire.
Gen Mohamed Farrar Aideed and Ali Mahdi Mohamed, the feuding clan-barons who
control parts of the divided capital Mogadishu, met for the first time in
more than a year. Afterwards, they shook hands, smiled and announced a
seven-point peace plan.
The meeting, organised by Mr Robert Oakley, the US ambassador-at-large, took
place in the temporary US embassy which was ringed by Marines and secured
from the air by Cobra helicopter gunships.
Both warlords, forced to the table by the speed and efficiency of the US and
French military deployment in the capital, said they had also agreed to
withdraw their armies from the streets, end hostile propaganda and demolish
the 'green line' which divides the city. The two will meet again today
aboard a French aid ship.
Many Somalis questioned how genuine the hasty reconciliation was, given the
deep bitterness which divides the two men and which had defeated the best
efforts of the United Nations to reach a settlement. Differences also
emerged as Mr Mahdi, the self-styled president, asked the US to disarm all
Somalis and to bring the UN deeper into the intervention - two steps
strongly resisted by Gen Aideed.
The US military build-up continued in Mogadishu with the arrival of more
troops. There were further incidents between Somalis and US and French
forces who have mounted impromptu road blocks across the city to help end
the piracy of relief food.
On day three of the military intervention, tempers flared as Somalis tested
the nerve and authority of the foreign troops. A few warning shots were
fired, a journalist was shot in the leg and another stabbed by increasingly
hostile Mogadishu residents.
Somalis also gathered at the site where French paratroopers shot dead two
Somalis who, the French alleged, tried to break through a roadblock on
Thursday night. UN representatives called for an inquiry into the incident.
David White, defence correspondent, reports from Brussels: The US plans to
withdraw most of its forces in three months, Mr Dick Cheney, US defence
secretary, said yesterday.
Speaking after a Nato defence ministers' meeting in Brussels, he said he
hoped that withdrawals could begin by late January through arrangements to
transfer authority in some areas to UN peacekeepers. However, certain
specialised US forces such as logistics troops and combat engineers might
have to stay longer.
Reuter adds from Little Rock, Arkansas: President-elect Bill Clinton said
last night that he could not put 'a fixed timetable' on the US operation.
City of death, Page 5
</TEXT>
