<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 92 / The Lex Column: Prudential
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Prudential's decision to shed the last of its commercial business more
or less completes the reshaping since Mr Mick Newmarch took charge in 1990.
As the shares have outperformed the market by 25 per cent in that time, the
market might reasonably wonder where the company goes from here. Yesterday's
4 per cent fall suggests more than a smidgeon of uncertainty.
For one thing, general reinsurance is still bleeding cash. The Pru's rating
will doubtless receive another boost if a buyer is ever found, but that
could be years away. Compared to the risks elsewhere in the sector, though,
Prudential is sitting pretty. While composite insurers look better geared to
recovery, mortgage indemnity claims could be a millstone well into the
middle of the decade.
With the estate agencies, commercial business and troublesome overseas
operations out of the way, Prudential's growth prospects turn on the
long-term savings business. The immediate outlook is rosy enough. The new
business boom of the early 1980s should feed into profits as 10-year
policies mature. That underpins the promise to increase the dividend this
year. Whether Mr Newmarch can keep new business flowing and expenses under
control is another matter. There are certainly signs of self-confidence.
Prudential's new accruals method of accounting for life profits makes the
new business performance more transparent. By introducing it, Mr Newmarch
has nailed his colours firmly to the mast.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
