<DOCNO>FT924-2393</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLMAOADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921212
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 92 / The Lex Column: Down with inflation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In different times the equity market might have responded more positively to
news that inflation had fallen to its lowest level in six years. Since the
chancellor appears to have ruled out further cuts in interest rates for the
time being, there is less cause for celebration. Besides, part of the fall
in the underlying rate to 3.6 per cent from 3.8 per cent reflects unusual
softness in food prices. That is unlikely to continue after January when the
green pound devaluation will start to be felt. Slowing inflation also
suggests that most businesses do not yet have sufficient confidence to push
aggressively for price rises. The deflationary effects of recession remain
strong.
Lower mortgage rates could see headline inflation dip below 2 per cent in
the first quarter. The difficult question is what will happen after that. On
one view, price pressures from devaluation could still be damped by falling
unit labour costs. A low headline rate would also reinforce the government's
effort to hold down public sector pay.
However the temptation for business to recoup lost margins with price
increases will surely become irresistible once real recovery is under way.
That is underlined by Ford's price increase this week. The budget, too,
could push up prices; the chancellor has already promised to claw back the
car tax with additional costs for the motorist. The suspicion lingers that
the lower the inflation rate falls now, the sharper will be its later
rebound. Perhaps that is why index-linked gilts reacted to November's
monthly fall in the retail prices with gains of around a quarter point.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
