<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 92 / International Company News: Pacific Telesis to spin off
wireless unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PACIFIC Telesis, the California-based local telephone company, yesterday
announced plans to spin off its wireless communications business in the
boldest move yet by one of the 'Baby Bell' telephone companies to cope with
increasing competition in the US telecommunications industry.
The decision, announced following a special board meeting in San Francisco,
means that the wireless business, one of the largest cellular telephone
operators in the US, will become totally independent from the local
telephone business, which serves most of California and parts of Nevada. The
wireless business also has significant interests in Germany, France and
other European markets.
Mr Sam Ginn, chairman, said the spin-off would enhance shareholder value by
creating separate, publicly traded companies able to react quickly to
changes in the telecommunications market.
It would also eliminate many of the financial, legal and regulatory
restraints to the group's growth.
Pacific Telesis is one of the seven ' Baby Bell' regional telephone
companies spun off in 1984 from AT&amp;T under a court-ordered break-up of the
group.
The Baby Bells face increasing competition from independent
telecommunications companies serving business clients, while themselves
remaining subject to heavy local regulation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
