<HEADLINE>
FT  12 DEC 92 / Tyson; cautious activist who advocates hardball: Michael
Prowse on Clinton appointees Laura D'Andrea Tyson and Robert Reich
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MS Laura D'Andrea Tyson, 45, a professor of economics and business at the
University of California at Berkeley, is the first woman to be nominated
head of the Council of Economic Advisers since the presidential advisory
body was established in 1946.
Educated at Smith College, she has a PhD from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. She has written extensively on trade and industrial policy, and
on the economies of eastern Europe. Her most recent book, Who's Bashing
Whom: Trade Conflict in High Technology Industries, was published last month
by the Institute for International Economics in Washington.
Within the economics profession, she has gained a reputation as one of most
intelligent critics of the free market economic policies in vogue during the
Reagan-Bush years. She describes herself as a 'cautious activist' and
believes the federal government should intervene more aggressively than in
the past to improve the performance of particular sectors.
In her latest book, she calls for targeted subsidies for strategic, high
valued added industries such as semiconductors and supercomputers, heavy
federal investment in civilian research and development, and generous tax
incentives for corporate research and development.
On trade policy she believes the US should play hardball, demanding
concessions from other countries when it opens markets. She says it should
respond to foreign subsidies with 'countervailing subsidies' for US
companies.
Ms Tyson believes the federal government should develop 'an institutional
capability for assessing competitive trends in high technology industries.'
She was one of the few academics willing to defend the 1986 semiconductor
trade deal between the US and Japan, which guaranteed foreign companies a
fixed share of the Japanese market. Many economists believe such 'managed
trade' agreements are a form of covert protection.
</TEXT>
