<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Bentsen man of action on domestic front
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ONE way or another, President Bill Clinton was going to have to deal with Mr
Lloyd Bentsen in order to get his economic programme through Congress. He
has chosen to do it with the senator from Texas on board his administration
as Treasury secretary rather than offshore as chairman of the Senate finance
committee.
Though generally described as middle-of-the-road, or, by Democratic party
standards, conservative, Mr Bentsen is not associated with any pronounced
economic philosophy. A lawyer by training, his reputation in Congress is
built mostly on an ability to compromise, detailed knowledge of the budget
and the tax code, and an inclination to favour business interests.
He is known to believe that the US does not save enough and favours a big
extension of personal pensions as one way to tackle this problem. His
business connections make him more inclined to promote economic growth than
to sit hard on inflation, which, broadly, is Mr Clinton's conviction. He
has, however, been sceptical about some aspects of health care reform, which
is high on the incoming president's agenda and important in bringing the
budget deficit under control.
Mr Bentsen's international experience is limited, much as was Mr James
Baker's when he took over the Treasury in President Ronald Reagan's second
term. In the mid-1980s, Mr Bentsen was in favour of a managed depreciation
of the dollar, but that was at a time when the US currency was under great
pressure, and he is a supporter of the North American Free Trade Agreement.
Beyond that, he has had little to say about the debt problem, assistance to
the former Soviet Union and co-ordinated international growth strategy and
is not well known by the senior bureaucrats of the International Monetary
Fund and World Bank in Washington.
But Mr Clinton has named him principally to get things done domestically. On
that Mr Bentsen has a proven track record.
See Observer
</TEXT>
