<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Panetta will speak for the deficit-sensitive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR LEON PANETTA has spent much of the past 15 years developing his
credentials as one of Congress's most know-ledgeable, intense and
intellectually curious experts on the US budget process.
As chairman of the House of Representatives budget committee for the past
four years, the California congressman was one of the Democrats' leaders in
budget summits with the Republican administration.
With the White House and Congress now about to come under the control of the
same party, there will be little need for budget summits. His Republican
admirers are not surprised, therefore, that he is taking the opportunity to
move to the executive branch as director of the Office of Management and
Budget.
Mr Panetta was originally a Republican himself, but he changed party shortly
after being fired by President Richard Nixon as head of the Office of Civil
Rights because of his complaints about how slowly the administration was
approaching desegregation.
First elected to Congress in 1976 from a district centred on Monterey, he is
now in his second stint on the budget committee where, unlike other House
committees, members serve only six years at a time.
He has long been a spokesman for deficit-sensitive Democrats, carrying the
lesson he learned from his father - an immigrant from Italy who always paid
cash - who 'kicked the hell' out of his 18-year-old son when he found he had
secretly acquired a credit card.
'He's a workhorse, and not a show-horse. He's not the kind of guy who sits
around and kisses babies or clips ribbons,' comments one friend. Taking an
administration job may allow Mr Panetta to acquire a Washington home of his
own. He now shares a two-bedroom house with three other Democratic
congressmen.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
