<DOCNO>FT924-2529</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AHBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921211
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Rivlin hawkish on budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIST and senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, Alice M Rivlin,
61, has been nominated as deputy budget director. She is best known in
Washington as the founding director of the congressional budget office,
established in 1975 to provide independent advice on budgetary matters for
Congress.
In the late 1960s she was an assistant secretary at the Department of
Health, Education and Welfare, and helped implement Lyndon Johnson's Great
Society programmes.
Ms Rivlin is a past president of the American Economics Association and a
past director of economic studies at Brookings, Washington's premier liberal
think-tank. She is a director of several US companies.
She has written extensively on the US economy, budget policy and many social
issues including health care.
Physically diminutive, she has a pithy speaking style and gained a
reputation for independence as CBO director. Her realistic forecasts often
infuriated both White House and congressional committees.
In her latest book, Reviving the American Dream, she argues for a radical
rethinking of the roles and financing of federal and state government. She
believes states should assume full responsibility for a 'productivity
agenda', which would include education, skill training, infrastructure and
other policies to improve national competitiveness. As a quid pro quo,
federal government would assume responsibility for health care.
On the budget policy, she is as hawkish as her boss, Mr Leon Panetta. She
has argued strongly for tough action to reduce the deficit.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2530</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AHAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921211
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Clinton brings in the economic heavyweights: Talented
line-up will attack budget deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GETTING legislation through Congress and reassuring Wall Street appear to
have been President-elect Bill Clinton's dominant concerns in assembling a
talented and remarkably conservative economic team.
As expected, the two top jobs go to Democratic congressional heavyweights,
Senator Lloyd Bentsen of Texas and Mr Leon Panetta, a congressman from
California, who were named treasury secretary and budget director. As former
chairmen of the Senate finance committee and the House budget committee
respectively, they appear ideally suited to shepherd sensitive economic and
social legislation through Congress.
Wall Street is strongly represented, with Mr Robert Rubin, a co-chairman of
Goldman Sachs, becoming special assistant to the president for economic
policy, and Mr Roger Altman, an investment banker at the Blackstone Group,
named as Mr Bentsen's deputy at the Treasury.
The only professional economist in the team announced yesterday was Ms Alice
Rivlin, a fellow at the Brookings Institution and a former director of the
Congressional Budget Office, who will serve as deputy to Mr Panetta at the
Office of Management and Budget.
The biggest surprise was that Mr Clinton did not name the chairman of the
Council of Economic Advisers in his first batch of appointments. In previous
administrations, the CEA chairman has served as part of a 'troika' of
advisers to the president, alongside the treasury secretary and budget
director.
But Mr Clinton said he intended the CEA to have 'more of an influence in
terms of ideas' than in the past. He also wanted to elevate the role in
economic policy-making of other departments, such as energy and commerce.
Speculation about CEA chair yesterday centred on Ms Laura D'Andrea Tyson, an
industrial and trade policy expert at the University of California at
Berkeley, and Mr Lawrence Summers, chief economist at the World Bank, who is
opposed by some environmentalists because of an insensitive memo he wrote at
the bank.
However, Mr Clinton's mention of the importance of ideas could indicate that
his old friend Mr Robert Reich, who heads the economic transition team, is
still in the running.
The biggest innovation was the appointment of Mr Rubin to head a new
economic council within the White House. This is intended to play a role
analogous to that of the National Security Council and represents an attempt
to bring economic policy to the same level of prominence within the White
House as foreign affairs and defence - all topics which have tended to
preoccupy past presidents.
Mr Clinton will chair the economic council, whose members will include
relevant cabinet officers, such as the commerce secretary, as well as the
other members of the economic team named yesterday. Some academics, however,
fear that the new council could overshadow the CEA.
Mr Rubin regards his main task as co-ordinating economic policy. Mr Clinton
yesterday compared his role to that of General Brent Scowcroft, President
George Bush's national security adviser, and played down the possibility of
any conflict between Mr Rubin and Mr Bentsen, making it clear that the
treasury secretary would be the administration's senior spokesman on
economics after the president.
The team boasts a wealth of experience and a long institutional memory. Mr
Bentsen and Mr Panetta have played leading roles for over a decade in
framing congressional economic and budget policies. Ms Rivlin is remembered
as a highly competent and fiercely independent director of the CBO from 1975
to 1983.
Mr Altman served in the Treasury during the Carter administration. Mr Rubin
has all-round financial expertise as co-chairman of one Wall Street's most
successful investment banks.
Mr Bentsen's widely trailed appointment as treasury secretary was welcomed
in US business and financial circles. If he and Mr Panetta have a weakness,
it is lack of experience in international economic policy-making. However,
the Wall Street appointees are both knowledgeable about foreign economies
and financial markets.
The overall composition of the team suggests considerable stress will be
laid on measures to improve the economy's long-term competitiveness. All
members of the team are known to regard budget deficit reduction as a
priority. The OMB duo of Mr Panetta and Ms Rivlin is likely to prove
especially hawkish on fiscal policy.
Mr Clinton was at pains yesterday to emphasise two points: he remains the
administration's chief economic decision maker, the 'ultimate arbiter' of
policy; and he puts a premium on co-operative teamwork - something obviously
lacking in the Bush administration.
He appeared justifiably pleased with his handiwork: on paper at least, he is
fielding the strongest economic team of any recent president, one which is
likely to gain the respect of Republicans as well as Democrats.
</TEXT>
