<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / International Company News: Goldman strategy will be
unchanged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR STEPHEN Friedman, co-chairman of Goldman Sachs, will become sole head of
the New York investment bank when Mr Robert Rubin, the firm's other joint
chief, becomes director of the Clinton administration's new National
Economic Council.
Goldman Sachs made clear last night that Mr Rubin's appointment, announced
by president-elect Bill Clinton yesterday, would mean no other changes in
the top management of the company.
Goldman's strategy has made the firm one of the most consistently successful
on Wall Street.
In a message to staff yesterday Mr Friedman said: 'Apart from normal
evolution, you should not expect any departures from the managerial or
strategic courses we have been on.'
The Clinton appointment brings to an end an unusually close working
relationship between Mr Rubin and Mr Friedman for much of their careers at
Goldman. They were appointed co-chief operating officers in 1987 and
co-chairmen in 1990.
Mr Rubin will detatch himself completely from the firm.
</TEXT>
