<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow declines despite good
economic data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
PROFIT-TAKING weighed on US share prices despite more good news on inflation
and jobs, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 11.62 at 3,312.19,
but off its lows for the day when the index had been down more than 20
points. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended 0.99 lower at
434.66, the Amex composite down 0.59 at 392.39 and the Nasdaq composite off
4.99 at 658.93. Turnover on the NYSE was 242m shares, and declines
outdistanced rises by 1,043 to 775.
Signs that the market's recent rally may be running out of steam were
evident when prices failed to rise after the Labor Department reported that
producer prices fell 0.2 per cent in November, following a 0.1 per cent
decline the previous month, and that weekly jobless claims in late November
fell by 38,000.
Both sets of data were better than analysts had expected. The producer
prices figure was particularly encouraging, as it confirmed that
inflationary pressures are not building up despite evidence that the
recovery is gathering pace.
The market failed to respond positively to the data, primarily because the
initial rush of investor demand that has powered several indices to new
highs over the past few weeks is clearly waning.
General Motors eased Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 33 3/8 on the news that the car
manufacturer faces a law suit filed on behalf of some purchasers of pick-up
trucks with fuel tanks located outside the frame. Other motor stocks were
also weaker, with Chrysler Dollars  3/4 lower at Dollars 32 1/4 and Ford
down Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 42 3/4 .
Equitable rose Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 13 3/4 in turnover of 1.8m shares on
news that the company had formed a strategic partnership with Unum, the
specialist Maine-based insurer, to sell Unum-designed individual disability
insurance products. Unum firmed Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 53 3/4 .
Chock Full O' Nuts rose Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 8 1/4 after reporting fiscal
first quarter net income of 12 cents a share, up from 5 cents a share a year
earlier. The company also said it expected profits for the full year 1993 to
come in above analysts' forecasts of 45 cents a share.
Delta Air Lines firmed Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 51 1/2 after the company said
that contrary to reports, it was not currently considering suspending its
quarterly dividend or planning job layoffs. On the Nasdaq market, Microsoft
fell Dollars 3 to Dollars 89 in volume of 2.8m shares on a downgrade from
Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette, which believes that the company will not exceed
analysts' earnings expectations. Hopes that the company would do just that
have been behind the recent surge in Microsoft shares.
Canada
TORONTO stocks partly recouped earlier losses, but still finished nearly 0.5
per cent lower after a heavy trading session. The TSE-300 fell 15.3 to
3,270.2 on volume of 44.7m shares valued at CDollars 351m. Declines outpaced
advances, 335 to 275, with 304 issues unchanged.
